# AES-128 Secure Image Transmission — STM32F407

> **Two-stage AES encryption project on bare-metal STM32F407 — progressing from basic ECB block cipher to a full hardware-RNG-keyed CBC image transmission system over UART.**

---

## Project Structure

```
stm32_aes_secure_image_uart/
├── 01_AES_ECB_Demo/        — Stage 1: basic AES-128 ECB encrypt/decrypt
│   ├── Src/
│   │   ├── main.c
│   │   └── aes.c
│   └── Inc/
│       ├── main.h
│       └── aes.h
└── 02_Secure_Image_Sender/  — Stage 2: hardware RNG + CBC image transmission
    ├── Src/
    │   ├── main.c
    │   ├── aes.c
    │   └── image_data.c
    └── Inc/
        ├── main.h
        ├── aes.h
        └── image_data.h
```

---

## Hardware

| Component | Details |
|---|---|
| MCU | STM32F407 (ARM Cortex-M4 @ 168 MHz) |
| SRAM | 192 kB |
| Flash | 512 kB |
| RNG | On-chip hardware random number generator |
| Interface | USART2 — 115200 baud, binary protocol |

---

## Stage 1 — AES-128 ECB Demo

A minimal proof-of-concept establishing baseline understanding of the AES block cipher on embedded hardware.

### What It Does

```
Plaintext (16 bytes)
        │
        ▼
  AES-128 ECB Encrypt  ← key: "STM32CryptoKey!!"
        │
        ▼
  Ciphertext (16 bytes)
        │
        ▼
  AES-128 ECB Decrypt
        │
        ▼
  Recovered Plaintext
        │
        ▼
  USART2 → PC terminal (original / encrypted / decrypted)
```

### Key Parameters

| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| AES mode | ECB (Electronic Codebook) |
| Key length | 128-bit (16 bytes) |
| Block size | 16 bytes |
| Baud rate | 115200 |

> **Note:** ECB mode encrypts each block independently — identical plaintext produces identical ciphertext. Intentionally used here for learning; CBC mode is used in Stage 2 for real security.

---

## Stage 2 — Secure Image Sender

A complete embedded-to-host secure data link — fresh cryptographic key and IV generated on every power-on, image encrypted in CBC mode, streamed over UART, and reconstructed on the host.

### What It Does

```
Power-On
    │
    ▼
Hardware RNG → 128-bit AES Key (random, unique per boot)
Hardware RNG → 128-bit IV     (random, unique per boot)
    │
    ▼
image_data[] (320×240 monochrome bitmap, 9600 bytes in Flash)
    │
    ▼
memcpy → RAM tx_buffer
    │
    ▼
AES-128 CBC Encrypt (key + IV)
    │
    ▼
UART Binary Stream:
  [16 bytes KEY] → [16 bytes IV] → [9600 bytes CIPHERTEXT]
    │
    ▼
Python Receiver (host PC)
  ├── Extract KEY (first 16 bytes)
  ├── Extract IV  (next 16 bytes)
  ├── AES-CBC Decrypt remaining bytes
  └── Reconstruct 320×240 bitmap → image file
```

### Key Parameters

| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| AES mode | CBC (Cipher Block Chaining) |
| Key length | 128-bit — hardware RNG generated |
| IV | 128-bit — hardware RNG generated |
| Image size | 9,600 bytes (320×240 × 1-bit monochrome) |
| Stream format | KEY → IV → CIPHERTEXT (binary) |
| Baud rate | 115200 |

### Why CBC over ECB?

CBC chains each block's encryption to the previous ciphertext block via XOR before encrypting. This means identical plaintext blocks produce different ciphertext — the image structure is completely hidden. Combined with a hardware-RNG key and IV that change every boot, no two transmissions are ever the same.

### Why Hardware RNG?

The STM32F407 has a dedicated on-chip RNG peripheral that sources entropy from analog noise in the silicon. This eliminates the need for a hardcoded or software-derived key — every power cycle produces a cryptographically fresh key and IV with no predictable pattern.

---

## Python Receiver

> **Note:** The Python receiver script was lost due to a system reinstall. The protocol is fully documented above — the receiver reads the first 16 bytes as the AES key, the next 16 bytes as the IV, and decrypts the remaining stream using AES-128 CBC to reconstruct the original bitmap.

A compatible receiver can be implemented in ~30 lines using `pyserial` and `pycryptodome`:

```python
import serial
from Crypto.Cipher import AES

ser = serial.Serial('COMx', 115200)

key  = ser.read(16)
iv   = ser.read(16)
data = ser.read(9600)

cipher = AES.new(key, AES.MODE_CBC, iv)
plain  = cipher.decrypt(data)

# Unpack 1-bit pixels → 320×240 image
```

